What is the right architecture for a schema and API validation tool that must operate at multiple levels of the software delivery lifecycle simultaneously — as a developer-facing CLI, as a CI/CD pipeline gate, as a pre-commit hook, and as a runtime request validator — when each context has different performance requirements, different acceptable false positive rates, and different failure semantics?

The developer CLI context rewards thoroughness over speed. A developer running validation interactively is willing to wait five seconds for a comprehensive report and expects detailed, actionable error messages with suggestions. False positives are tolerable if they come with explanations. The failure mode here is not blocking work — a developer can choose to ignore a warning.

The CI/CD gate context requires reliability and determinism above all else. The same spec must produce the same result every time. Performance matters (slow CI frustrates developers), but thoroughness matters more. A false positive that blocks a deployment is a serious problem. The acceptable false positive rate approaches zero for errors; warnings may be tolerated. The check must complete in under 30 seconds for an average API spec.

The pre-commit hook context must complete in under two seconds or developers will disable it. Only the most critical, high-confidence checks should run here. Any check that has non-trivial false positive rates must be excluded. The hook must fail gracefully if validation dependencies are unavailable.

The runtime validator context (validating live requests/responses against an OpenAPI spec) requires microsecond-level latency overhead. Only the fastest validation paths are acceptable. The schema must be pre-compiled. Error reporting must be minimal to avoid log volume explosions. The failure semantics are different: a validation failure is not a developer error but a potential security or data quality incident.

Think through how these contexts should be modeled in a tool's architecture. Should they share a single validation engine with configurable strictness and timeout budgets, or should they be separate implementations optimized for each context? What is the right abstraction for a "validation profile" that encodes context-appropriate settings? How should the tool handle the case where a check is appropriate in CI but too slow for pre-commit?
